passages.text: Cutting profit estimates on higher costs; FY6/26 profit growth to be limited amid increased investment; high hurdle to achieving Rule of 40; Sell
4478.T 12m Price Target: ¥2,900 Price: ¥3,135 Downside: 7.5%

We update our earnings estimates for freee to reflect FY6/25 and 4Q6/25 (April- June) results (see our report). We cut our FY6/26- FY6/27 operating profit estimates by ¥2.3 bn and ¥1.4 bn, respectively (and introduce FY6/28 estimates), reflecting larger- than- expected growth investment, mainly in personnel, development, and sales promotion expenses. Given the start of a new fiscal year, we roll over the base period for our DCF model to FY6/35 (final year in our model) from FY6/34. With this, we raise our 12- month target price slightly, to ¥2,900 from ¥2,800. However, we expect the trend in near- term profits to remain subdued.

We forecast FY6/26 adjusted operating profits (operating profits + share- based compensation expenses/amortization of intangible assets related to M&A) of ¥2.5 bn (+33%/+¥0.62 bn yoy), in line with guidance for ¥2.46 bn- 2.5 bn. Net adds of enterprise users (qoq) have been below the year- earlier level for three consecutive quarters, and freee plans to strengthen its sales and development capabilities to drive medium- term growth. We thus expect growth investment to remain high for the time being, and as in FY6/25, any profits exceeding guidance are likely to be reinvested in growth. While we think this strategy is reasonable from a medium- term growth perspective, we note that short- term profit improvement is likely to be limited.

The company expects to continue hiring aggressively in FY6/26, and accordingly the impact of higher personnel costs from this hiring will be fully reflected in FY6/27. We thus expect costs to remain high in FY6/27. Growth investment is poised to remain high in FY6/26- FY6/27 as freee aims to achieve its FY6/28 Rule of 40 financial target (sales growth + adjusted free cash flow (FCF) margin >40%). be challenging. The shares look overvalued to us in light of the near- term profit outlook (trading at P/Es of 46x/26x our estimates three/five years out, applying a normal tax rate), and we maintain our Sell- rating.

We forecast FY6/26 sales of 1.6 bn (+25% yoy) and adjusted operating profits (operating profit share- based compensation expenses/amortization of intangible assets related to M&A) of \(\yen 2.5\) bn (+33%/+\\$0.62 bn yoy), both in line with guidance for \(\yen 40.9\) bn- 41.6 bn and \(\yen 2.46\) bn- 2.5 bn (Exhibit 1). We expect sales to grow steadily, driven by the enterprise segment (a key focus for free) and supported by an increase in the cloud penetration rate. While the company's assumption for ARPU in the midsize enterprise segment looks somewhat bullish, we think free can achieve the upper end of its sales guidance range given market growth and the pace of customer acquisition.

In terms of yoy growth, we expect sustained customer acquisition via accounting firms in business with SMEs, and higher ARPU as clients switch from bookkeeping plans to higher- tier plans. In business with midsize enterprises, we expect cross- selling of accounting and payroll software to be successful, in addition to user growth driven by market expansion. However, given industry trends and the competitive environment, we think it will be difficult to speed up the pace of net adds for enterprise users. Given this, we forecast corporate ARR (annual recurring revenue) of \(\yen 32.7\) bn (+23% yoy) at end- FY6/26, with 268,670 users (+15% yoy) and ARPU of \(\yen 121,840\) (+7%). While we expect ARR growth to slow as the benefits of price hikes drop out, we think strong growth will continue.
Exhibit 1: We expect operating profits to expand in FY6/26, but increase likely to be limited by higher growth investment Sales and adjusted operating profits
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Meanwhile, we expect operating profits to improve only modestly (+\\$0.62 bn yoy) owing to higher growth investment, mainly in R&D expenses and sales & marketing (sales staff personnel costs and advertising/sales promotion expenses). While profits could exceed guidance depending on the pace of increase in growth investment, free plans to ramp up growth investment for the time being to achieve its Rule of 40 financial target in FY6/28 (sales growth + adjusted FCF margin >40%). We thus assume that any profits exceeding guidance will be reinvested in growth (as was the case in FY6/25).
Given this, while we expect quarterly profits to fluctuate based on how much growth investment increases, we think full- year profits will be largely in line with guidance.

Growth investment is set to include higher personnel costs (on increased hiring) and R&D expenses, as well as higher advertising expenses on stepped- up promotional activities. The company plans to maintain the pace of hiring in FY6/26 at around the FY6/25 level, expecting to increase headcount by a net \(+200\) (from 1,901 at end- FY6/25 to 2,100 at end- FY6/26). We assume that sales staff and development engineers will each account for around half of the increase. While labor productivity is improving with the use of generative AI, freee plans to further strengthen its sales structure to drive sales growth and increase market share. It also intends to strengthen its development engineering and R&D structure to enhance its lineup of industry- specific products. The company plans to focus on industries where it has had a limited presence (e.g., manufacturing and retail), and it will need to increase development of related functions, as these industries require industry- specific capabilities. We thus expect R&D expenses and software asset depreciation expenses (cost of sales) to increase.

Given the above, we forecast SG&A expense increases of ¥5.95 bn/22% yoy, with rises of ¥1.96 bn/41% yoy in R&D expenses, 2.57 bn/14% yoy in sales & marketing expenses, and ¥1.42 bn/33% yoy) in G&A (general and administrative expenses; Exhibit 2). The positive impact on profits from the higher capitalization ratio for R&D expenses (FY6/24: 10- 15%; FY6/25: around 50%) will drop out, and we expect R&D expenses to increase organically in FY6/26 as freee strengthens the development structure. However, as a percentage of sales, we expect SG&A expenses to decline to 78.6% (down 1.8 pp yoy), with R&D expenses rising to 16.1% (up 1.9 pp yoy), sales & marketing expenses falling to 48.8% (down 4.5 pp yoy), and G&A expenses rising to 13.7% (up 0.8 pp yoy). We thus expect cost efficiencies to improve gradually, mainly in sales & marketing, even as freee ramps up growth investment. Meanwhile, we look for the gross profit margin to trend downward over the medium term (FY6/26- FY6/28) due to higher software asset depreciation expenses.
Exhibit 2: Costs to increase in FY6/26, mainly in R&D and sales & marketing, but cost efficiencies to improve gradually as a % of sales SG&A expense breakdown by cost component
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

However, we expect costs to remain high, as the impact of higher personnel costs from hiring during FY6/26 will be fully reflected in FY6/27, and growth investment is set to continue. The adjusted free cash flow margin (excluding the impact of changes in credit card business advances and M&A-related income/expenses), which is a key medium-term financial target for free, is difficult to estimate from the outside, making the target challenging to assess. However, given sales growth momentum and profitability trends, we think achieving the Rule of 40 (sales growth + adjusted free cash flow (FCF) margin \(>40\%\) ) in FY6/28 will be quite challenging. The likelihood of achieving this target would increase if free raises prices again, but we think this is unlikely in FY6/26, as it already raised prices for enterprise customers in FY6/25.

Investment Thesis - freee K.K.freee K. K. (Sell) is a software vendor that provides cloud- native enterprise resource planning (ERP) services centered on back- office functions, primarily accounting and payroll software. Its technological strength lies in simplifying data sharing and other functions across businesses and improving business efficiency by introducing integrated ERP system architecture. We expect the ERP cloud penetration rate to trend upward in Japan against the backdrop of lower costs, increased convenience (including open systems accessible by external entities), and expanded functionality via API integration. However, we expect valuations (P/E and DCF) to remain high even after a swing to profit at the adjusted operating line given intensifying competition in the cloud ERP market and our assumption that upfront spending aimed at acquiring new customers will continue for the time being.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
